  "text": "In general, the gel analyses of whole muscle cross sections reflected adaptations in a direction similar to, although to a lesser magnitude, those observed for the immunohistochemical analyses of a sample of fibers from the deep region of the muscle. These apparent discrepancies between the gel and immunohistochemical analyses could reflect several factors. For example, although a fiber may contain multiple MHC isoforms as demonstrated immunohistochemically, the amount of newly expressed MHCs in hybrid fibers may be very small. In addition, the superficial region of the plantaris, a large proportion of the total cross section of the muscle, is composed predominantly of fast fibers that may have adapted somewhat differently to the overload stimulus. In any case, the gel analyses suggest that a shift from faster to slower MHC isoforms occurred in the superficial as well as the deep region of the muscle. In addition, a conversion from fast to slow fibers has been observed previously in both the deep (from 16 to 48%) and the superficial (from 3 to 19%) regions of the plantaris after 9-12 wk of overload [CITATION_1] . The changes in the percentage of total MHC observed in the present study after 10 wk of FO are consistent with the results of Fauteck and Kandarian (10) after 5 wk of FO. They found the following shifts from control to FO: 11 to 16% for type I, 14 to 24% for type IIa, 36 to 42% for type IIx, and 39 to 18% for type IIb.",
